<title>
Reducing amyloid plaque burden via ex vivo gene delivery of an Abeta-degrading protease: a novel therapeutic approach to Alzheimer disease.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
he pathologic hallmarks of lzheimer disease () are extracellular plaques of amyloid-² protein (²) and intraneuronal neurofibrillary tangles of tau protein, both of which accumulate in brain regions mediating memory and cognition [1]. ll known early-onset, inherited forms of  arise from mutations in the ²-amyloid precursor protein (), from which the ² peptide is generated, or the presenilins, which are the proteases that effect the cleavage of , which liberates ². oth amyloid plaques and soluble ² oligomers are believed to have neurotoxic effects [2,3], and evidence suggests that ² neurotoxicity can promote neurofibrillary tangle formation [4,5]. hough approved treatments for  ameliorate only the symptoms, potentially disease-modifying interventions under development focus on therapeutically lowering ² production [6] or enhancing ² clearance [7,8].
he role of ² degradation in the clearance of the ² peptide is becoming more broadly understood and appreciated, with the proteases neprilysin [9], insulin-degrading enzyme [10,11], endothelin-converting enzymes 1 and 2 [12], plasmin [13], and cathepsin  [14] all capable of regulating ² levels in vivo. upporting a therapeutic function for ²-degrading proteases, both transgenic overexpression [15] and direct viral vector injection [14,16,17] of these enzymes have been shown to potently lower ² levels and plaque burden and reduce ²-associated neuropathology. he applicability of these approaches for  treatment in humans is uncertain, and alternative methods of gene delivery merit exploration.
n ex vivo gene therapy, cells are taken from a patient, genetically modified in vitro, then implanted back into the patient to exert their new salutary effects. his approach has produced therapeutic improvements in experimental models of human diseases and conditions including hemophilia [18], retinal degeneration [19], cancer [20], spinal cord injury [21], myopathy [22], ischemia [23], arkinson disease [24], untington disease [25], amyotrophic lateral sclerosis [26], and lzheimer disease [27]. everal of these potential treatments have advanced to human trials [28β€“31], with encouraging outcomes for patients. n a recent hase  clinical trial, autologous fibroblasts from  patients were modified to produce nerve growth factor and implanted into the forebrain, where they enhanced cholinergic function [28]. hese efforts demonstrate the feasibility of ameliorating cholinergic cell death by providing trophic support using an ex vivo gene delivery approach. owever, because ²-mediated synaptic function and cytotoxicity are likely to be upstream of neurotransmitter abnormalities in , enhancing ² clearance represents a more attractive target for gene therapy in this disorder.
eprilysin () is a type  transmembrane protein bound to the cell membrane, where it normally degrades ² intracellularly and on the cell surface [32]. erebral  levels have been reported to decrease with age and in  [33,34], which may contribute to disease pathogenesis by compromising ² catabolism. s an approach to elevate  levels and improve the enzyme's access to extracellular ², we replaced the transmembrane domain of  with a signal peptide, which produced a soluble and secreted form of , termed s. NEP. We then used ex vivo gene delivery utilizing syngenic primary fibroblasts to introduce sNEP into the brains of APP transgenic mice that had advanced plaque deposition and studied the effect of this protein on brain amyloid pathology.
