<sections.3>
Discussion
arious approaches to lowering ² levels within the brain have come to represent the central focus in  therapeutic development. n this study, we describe the use of ex vivo gene therapy as a viable approach to reducing ² levels utilizing a modified ²-degrading protease. eplacing the transmembrane domain of the normally membrane-anchored  with a signal peptide resulted in the robust secretion of an enzymatically active protease. hen syngenic fibroblasts modified to produce s. NEP were engrafted into aged APP transgenic mice, the majority of the plaque burden surrounding the graft site was proteolytically cleared. Distal to the graft, in both the medial and lateral hippocampus, significant reductions in plaque burden were also observed as a result of sNEP gene delivery. These results demonstrate the utility of locally elevating the expression of a secreted AΞ²-degrading protease as a potential therapeutic approach for AD.
The finding that sNEP was able to reduce plaque burden distal to the graft site may be explained by the diffusion of the sNEP enzyme through the parenchyma, by diffusion of soluble forms of AΞ² toward the graft (which may thus be serving as an AΞ² sink), or both of these mechanisms. Because of the low sensitivity of available anti-NEP antibodies, we were unable to detect sNEP diffusion farther than β�Ό800 ΞΌm from the graft site, nor could we detect the very low (Figure 1A) endogenous NEP levels expressed by neural tissue [51].
Potential side effects of sNEP expression may arise from the degradation of NEP substrates other than AΞ² present in the brain, such as enkephalins. Though studies explicitly searching for such side effects were not performed here, no adverse phenotype was reported in NEP transgenic mice that were protected from AΞ²-induced premature death [15], and in this study we observed no enhanced astrocytosis in response to sNEP expression.
A major obstacle to translating the ex vivo methods used in this study into a human disease therapy is the larger dimensions of the human brain, which might require an elevation in AΞ²-degrading activity throughout a much broader area. However, our experiment involved just a 28 d exposure to the sNEP-secreting cells, and we found these primary cells to maintain transgene expression in vitro for over a year. One approach to the problem of optimal diffusion of the gene product is to implant the cells where they may have the best access to circulating AΞ², such as in the cerebrospinal fluid or the ventricular wall. Several studies have reported the successful use of encapsulated cell implants that allow for diffusion of therapeutic factors into biological fluids, including cerebrospinal fluid [29,30]. By analogy to the peripheral sink hypothesis for AΞ² immunotherapy [52], it may also be feasible and attractive to implant genetically modified cells into peripheral compartments (e.g., the peritoneal cavity or skeletal muscle), where they may substantially increase the AΞ²-degrading capacity of the periphery and thus increase the rate of efflux of AΞ² across the bloodβ€“brain barrier. Moreover, some of the secreted sNEP provided by such a peripheral implant may reach the brain and cerebrospinal fluid to help decrease brain AΞ² levels directly. The existence of a subset of hematopoietic cells capable of infiltrating the brain and surrounding plaques has been described [53,54]. Though these cells may not efficiently degrade AΞ² themselves, if they could be modified to express an AΞ²-degrading protease in a manner similar to the approach we report here, they may provide an anatomically targeted means for local AΞ² elimination.
In summary, our findings demonstrate that ex vivo gene delivery of an AΞ²-degrading protease rapidly lowers hippocampal AΞ² plaque burden in a mouse model of Alzheimer disease. Ex vivo gene delivery and other strategies to elevate AΞ²-degrading activity in Alzheimer patients warrant further investigation as potential therapeutic approaches to treat this common and devastating disease.
